and something that was known but no one really talked about a lot was there were stakeholders

00:29:55.400 --> 00:30:01.880
who saw data scientists as a very expensive way to prove what they wanted to prove.

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:11.000
And they either didn't care what the answer was or wanted us to come to a specific conclusion.

00:30:11.719 --> 00:30:16.760
What are some strategies that you use to either massage or manage their expectations,

00:30:17.319 --> 00:30:22.439
manage around them, or just in general, how to navigate that minefield of a situation?

00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:38.520
So, first is you need to establish trust. So, you need to make sure that they trust you,

00:30:38.520 --> 00:30:46.119
because if they don't trust you, nothing will change. In order to build that trust,

00:30:47.319 --> 00:30:53.719
you need to understand what they care about. What are their goals? What are their pain points?

00:30:53.719 --> 00:31:02.280
What are their fears? What are their hopes? So, do that. Trust is basically

00:31:05.560 --> 00:31:10.680
three things that you need to have. The first is, and this is probably the most important,

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:18.920
is you need to show that you care for the other person. The second is, so that's the care part,

00:31:18.920 --> 00:31:25.479
the second is you need to have, the other person needs to feel that you're competent.

00:31:28.119 --> 00:31:36.199
So, the other person, you can bring this across with your profile, with what you have done before,

00:31:36.199 --> 00:31:42.520
who you have helped before. And the last part is the character. And I think this is really

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:52.119
important. You need to basically come across as a trustworthy person that wants to do the right

00:31:52.119 --> 00:32:05.160
things. And I know kind of, interestingly, especially kind of in the academic research

00:32:05.160 --> 00:32:12.280
area, that is kind of very, very common, exactly also what you described, that people want to get

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:25.800
the P values they need so that they can publish it. You need to help them understand what are the

00:32:25.800 --> 00:32:33.800
costs, what are the risks, and these kind of different things. And that you are not

00:32:34.359 --> 00:32:46.520
policing them, but helping them. So, in many pharma companies, the statisticians are,

00:32:48.119 --> 00:32:58.839
you know, behave like the P value police. Yeah. And that's not helpful. Yeah. That way, you

00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:04.760
exclude yourself, and you make yourself basically vulnerable for being outsourced.

00:33:05.719 --> 00:33:14.199
So, much better is understanding what is the overall risk for making a wrong decision,

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:21.400
and clearly kind of understanding this risk and communicating this risk.

